case_summary:
A 26-year-old man presented with a 1-week history of a confluent red macular rash on his face, neck, and upper chest, associated with sore throat, nausea, palpitations, fever, and malaise. He had fever to 38.7  degreesC, tachycardia to 130 bpm with a systolic murmur, and left hypochondrial pain. Examination revealed multiple tender head-and-neck lymph nodes. The rash, which began on the neck, spread to the face and back; it was blanching and mildly pruritic, with less pronounced involvement of the arms, legs, and abdomen.  
One month earlier, he had developed right-knee monoarthritis with elevated ESR (65 mm/h), CRP (92 mg/L), and synovitis on arthrocentesis; ANA and ANCA were negative. Sulfasalazine (500 mg five times daily) was initiated but stopped by the patient after 23 days when fever and rash appeared. He had no other chronic medications or allergies.  
Laboratory tests showed hemoglobin 11.6 g/dL; AST 78 U/L, ALT 224 U/L, LDH 533 U/L, GGT 132 U/L, alkaline phosphatase 145 U/L;
